dict.string: Speech production: Articulatory phonetics examines the physiology of how we use our bodies to produce speech.
Physical correlates of speech sounds: Acoustic phonetics looks at the physical properties of speech sounds.
Speech perception: Perceptual acoustics examines how we interpret/perceive the sound waves of speech.
The speech signal is continuous
Speech is fleeting
The articulators aren't visible
Challenges Phoneticians Face
Phonetic transcription: Linguistics have developed several systems for writing down all the minute details of speech sounds. We call this phonetic transcription.

Computational analysis: Linguists have developed computational algorithms fro analyzing the physical properties of the sound waves of speech sounds. We can look at the frequency, amplitude, and duration of speech sounds in great detail.
Other techniques: Ultrasounds and palaeography to "see" inside the mouth; fMRI and EEG to measure brain function.
How to tackle these challenges
problem: few languages have a one-to-one correlation between symbol and sound.
*one symbol for one sound
solution: The International Phonetic Alphabet
we need a precise system of representation for all the sounds of all the world's languages
the orthography (or writing system) of English is well suited for reading and writing.
Inadequacy of Orthography
1. force air out of lungs
2. send that air between your vocal cords (folds) in your larynx located at the bottom of your throat.
3. use primary articulators (tongue and lips) to manipulate the shape of the vocal tract to change the speech sound.
basics of speaking
vocal tract: like a trumpet or saxophone
sagittal section: a diagram of the head as though cut in two from front to back
voiced sounds vs voiceless sounds, related to the states of the Glottis
Anatomy/Physiology of Speech
bilabials: both lips together
labiodentals: lower lip and upper teeth
interdental: tongue tip between teeth
alveolars: tongue tip and alveolar ridge
palatal: tongue blade and hard palate
velar: tongue dorsum and soft palate
uvular: tongue and uvula (no English sounds)
glottal: vocal cords
2. Place of Articulation
stops: airstream from the mouth is completely stopped and then released in a single burst. also called plosives
fricatives: airstream is partially obstructed causing frication/turbulence in the airstream
affricates: a combination of stop followed by a fricative
Nasalization: to produce nasal sounds, make a full closure in the oral cavity and lower our velum to allow air to escape through the nose.
nasals: complete closure in the mouth. airflow escapes through nose
liquids: some constriction/obstruction, but not enough to create frication/turbulence.
glides: very little constriction/obstruction
approximants: more vowel-like consonants.
six different manners
3. Manner of Articulation
3 Key properties of English consonants
Consonants are sounds made with complete or partial obstruction of the oral tract (i.e., the flow of air is either stopped completely or limited)

4 key properties of English Vowel
Vowels are sounds made with very little obstruction in the oral tract (i.e., the air passes rather freely)
